Title:  RFI - DOI ITOM/ITSM/ITAM Software Solution
Received Date:  02/06/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  381 ELDEN STREET SUITE 4000 HERNDON VA 20170
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
RFI amendment 1 issued as follows: 1. Include the NAICs code 2. Include the Product Service Code 3. Include the CO contact information 4. Correct the typo in the RFI attachment to reflect the correct DOI RFI number to "DOIDFBO200007". Original Notice Posted Feb 04, 2020 under Special Notice: This sources sought notice is issued solely for information and planning purposes - it does not constitute an invitation for bid, request for quotation, request for proposal, or an obligation on behalf of the Government or a promise to issue a solicitation in the future. The Government is not seeking proposals and will not accept unsolicited proposals at this time. Vendors responding to this notice are advised that the U.S. Government will not pay for any information or administrative costs incurred in response to this sources sought notice; all costs associated with responding to this notice will be solely at the interested party's expense. Not responding to this notice does not preclude participation in any future solicitation, if issued. Interested parties are responsible for CLEARLY MARKING proprietary or competition sensitive information contained in their response. No classified, confidential, or sensitive information should be included in your response. Please be advised that all submissions become Government property and will not be returned. Marketing brochures and/or generic company literature will not be considered and shall not be sent in response to this notice. The purpose of this RFI is to utilize industry feedback to assist DOI in the improvement of requirements documents and in the development of an acquisition strategy and potential solicitation for the "Single Ticketing System (STS)". DOI is currently contemplating the use of a single vendor Indefinite Delivery, Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) or blanket purchase agreement (BPA) with a 5 to 10 year duration depending on the vehicle chosen. This RFI will be used to: 1) Identify vendors that are capable of providing high performance outcomes. 2) Obtain industry experience, best practices, recommendations, and lessons learned from performance in a single vendor environment for scope similar to DOI's requirement. 3) Finalize the Government's requirements documents (i.e., IDIQ, Statement of Objectives (SOO), Technical Exhibits [TEs], Quality Assurance Surveillance Plan (QASP), Service Level Agreements (SLAs), as well as other documentation as applicable). 4) After reviewing the results of the RFI/Sources sought notice, the Government may meet with a limited number of potential industry partners to gather additional market information. Scope of DOI ITOM/ITSM/ITAM Software Solution: The U.S. Department of Interior (DOI) is seeking a software solution that will provide information technology operations management (ITOM), service management (ITSM) and asset management (ITAM) capabilities for approximately 80,000 end users. The solution must be a commercial off the shelf (COTS) product, although requirements may dictate customization. The solution will allow DOI to combine its ITSM and ITAM processes.

The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) Glenn Research Center (GRC) intends to issue a Request for Proposals (RFP) for Professional, Administrative, Computational, and Engineering Services contract (PACE V). Agency Bid No.:  RFP 20-145 NM
Title:  DTD Asset Management Plan Refinements & Implementation
Received Date:  02/06/2020
Close Date:  03/11/2020  02:00 PM
Purchase Type:  Term Contract: 06/01/2020 - 05/31/2021
Estimated Amount:  400000
Delivery Date:  Not Stated
Special Notices:  Questions due date: 02/19/2020 - All or None Award
Specifications:
Objective The Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT), through its Performance and Asset Management Branch (PAMB) in its Division of Transportation Development (DTD), seeks services to update, refine and develop additional content for its risk-based Transportation Asset Management Plan (TAMP) and to ensure the plan continues to meet federal requirements. Additionally, this project will assist CDOT in advancing its asset management program. Introduction/Background CDOT's PAMB is responsible for reporting on the performance of the State of Colorado's transportation system. PAMB also informs CDOT's strategic planning and decision-making by providing tools that measure, analyze, forecast and communicate to staff and other transportation stakeholders the performance of CDOT's programs and investment decisions. To fulfill these responsibilities, PAMB produces several reports required by statute, as well as voluntary reports and performance-measurement tools. PAMB also coordinates CDOT's asset management efforts, including efforts that inform budget-setting for assets, as well as project selection. CDOT's asset management program includes 12 assets, including bridges, pavement, signals and others. PAMB works with a consultant to operate its Asset Investment Management System (AIMS), a tool that models investment inputs and performance outcomes for 11 of CDOT's 12 asset programs. CDOT's Transportation Asset Management Oversight Committee sets the strategic direction for asset management in CDOT. CDOT's Transportation Asset Management Working Committee manages implementation of asset management strategies. CDOT's Transportation Asset Management Risk Task Force is to advance risk and resiliency practices within CDOT's asset management program. The Moving Ahead for Progress in the 21st Century Act (MAP-21), the federal transportation authorization passed in 2012, required state departments of transportation (DOTs) to develop and implement risk-based asset management plans for the National Highway System (NHS) to improve or preserve the condition of the assets and the performance of the system. FHWA rulemaking established processes that state DOTs must use to develop their plans, requirements for the form and content of the resulting plans, implementation procedures, and procedures for FHWA oversight. Even before MAP21 became law, CDOT had embraced asset management as an important business practice for maintaining assets in a state of good repair over the long term with the least investment of resources. Since 2011, for example, CDOT's asset managers have been working with versions of CDOT's Asset Investment Management System (AIMS) to develop budget scenarios and explore the relationship between funding and performance. Additionally, CDOT developed its first asset management plan in 2013 and continues to develop and implement risk-based asset management as the official approach for strategic preservation of CDOT's assets. MAP-21 required state DOTs to submit an "initial" TAMP to FHWA by April 30, 2018. The "initial" TAMP was used by FHWA to determine if the development processes and investment strategies being used were in line with statutory requirements and to provide feedback where gaps may have existed. CDOT submitted its initial TAMP on April 30, 2018 and received FHWA certification on July 31, 2018. MAP-21 also requires state DOTs to submit a "complete" TAMP to FHWA by June 30, 2019. The complete TAMP is to include any refinements identified by FHWA in its review of the "initial" TAMP. CDOT submitted its "complete" TAMP to FHWA on June 30, 2019. Going forward, CDOT must update and resubmit its TAMP to FHWA for a process certification at least every 4 years (next TAMP due July 31, 2022) or when CDOT makes significant updates to its TAMP or TAMP development processes. FHWA also makes an annual consistency determination based on the most recent TAMP and any documentation submitted by CDOT to demonstrate implementation of the TAMP. For the annual consistency determination, FHWA verifies CDOT is using the investment strategies in its TAMP to make progress toward achievement of its targets for NHS asset condition and performance and to support progress toward the national goals for pavement and bridge assets. The selected consultant will assist CDOT in meeting these FHWA requirements. CDOT realizes that Transportation Asset Management (TAM) is a process of continual improvement and is more critical than ever for maintaining the quality of Colorado's transportation infrastructure in a cost-effective manner. The selected consultant will share CDOT's ongoing commitment to asset management and help define the path forward for CDOT's asset management program. Scope of Work This project will accomplish the following: Ensuring CDOT continues to meet TAMP federal reporting requirements, andAssisting CDOT in advancing its asset management program. This project will require the selected consultant to collaborate with: -CDOT Project ManagersPAMB Asset Management Analyst and PAMB Manager;CDOT Asset Managers for Surface Treatment, Bridge, Maintenance, Road Equipment, ITS, Geohazards, Buildings, Tunnels, Culverts, Walls, Signals, and Rest Areas;Other CDOT staff, such as staff in the Division of Accounting and Finance, Program Management Office and the Multimodal Planning Branch;CDOT consultant on PAMB's Asset Investment Management System (AIMS);Transportation Asset Management Oversight Committee;Transportation Asset Management Working Committee;Transportation Asset Management Risk Task Force;Metropolitan Planning Organization (MPO) representatives.; andFHWA representatives. Selected consultant will be expected to document via technical memos all new and revised processes related to CDOT's asset management program.
